<h1>Problem 607 - 2019 IMOSL, C6</h1>
<h2 class='difficulty'>Difficulty: 8</h2>
<p>Let \(n>1\) be an integer. Suppose we are given \(2n\) points in the plane such that no three of them are collinear. The points are to be labelled \(A_1\), \(A_2\), \(\dots\), \(A_{2n}\) in some order. We then consider the \(2n\) angles \(\angle A_1A_2A_3\), \(\angle A_2A_3A_4\), \(\dots\), \(\angle A_{2n-1}A_{2n}A_1\), \(\angle A_{2n}A_1A_2\). We measure each angle in the way that gives the smallest positive value (i.e. between \(0^{\circ}\) and \(180^{\circ}\)). Prove that there exists an ordering of the given points such that the resulting \(2n\) angles can be separated into two groups with the sum of one group of angles equal to the sum of the other group.</p>
